Q1. Introduction to Software Composition Analysis (SCA) – Security Case Study (15 Marks)
Introduction

Software Composition Analysis (SCA) is a security technique used to identify, analyze, and manage open-source and third-party software components used in an application.

Modern applications use many ready-made libraries and frameworks. If any of these components contain vulnerabilities, attackers can exploit them.

SCA helps organizations detect such risks early.

Why SCA is Important in FinTech

FinTech applications handle:

Payments
Banking transactions
Personal data
Sensitive financial records

Using insecure third-party components can cause:

Data breaches
Financial fraud
Compliance violations
Loss of customer trust
Security Case Study: FinTech Payment Application
Background

A FinTech company develops a mobile wallet app using:

Open-source authentication libraries
Encryption frameworks
Payment APIs

To save time, developers use third-party libraries without proper security checks.

Security Problem

One logging library used in the app is:

Outdated
Has a known vulnerability (CVE)

An attacker exploits this weakness and:

Accesses transaction logs
Steals customer payment data
Performs unauthorized transactions
Impact of Attack
Financial loss to customers
Reputation damage
Legal action from regulators
PCI DSS violations
Customer trust loss
Role of SCA in Solving the Problem

The company implements SCA in its development process.

Steps Followed
SCA tool scans the application
Identifies all third-party components
Checks known vulnerabilities
Flags risky libraries
Suggests secure versions
Stops deployment until fixed
Outcome After SCA
Vulnerable library replaced
Application secured before release
Compliance achieved
No further breaches
Better trust and security
Benefits of SCA
Early vulnerability detection
Prevents supply-chain attacks
Improves software security
Supports DevSecOps
Helps regulatory compliance
Examples of SCA Tools
OWASP Dependency-Check
Snyk
Black Duck
Mend (WhiteSource)
Conclusion

SCA is an essential security practice for modern software development. It protects applications by identifying risky third-party components before deployment.

Q2 (a) What is a Challenge When Applying a Shift Left Approach? (15 Marks)
Introduction

Shift Left means moving testing and security to the early stages of software development instead of checking only at the end.

Main Challenge

A major challenge is lack of security knowledge in development teams.

Developers may be good at coding but may not have enough cybersecurity skills.

Other Challenges
Increased workload in early stages
Tool integration difficulties
False positives from security tools
Resistance to process changes
Coordination issues between teams
Conclusion

The biggest challenge in Shift Left is combining fast development with early security practices.

Q2 (b) Why Do DevOps Recommend Shift Left Testing Principles?
Reasons
1. Early Bug Detection

Problems are found during coding.

2. Lower Cost

Fixing issues early is cheaper.

3. Faster Releases

Less rework means quicker delivery.

4. Better Quality

Continuous testing improves reliability.

5. Improved Security

Vulnerabilities are found before release.

6. Supports CI/CD

Works well with automation pipelines.

7. Less Production Failure

Reduces crashes and downtime.

Example

If a payment app checks security during coding, it avoids failures after launch.

Conclusion

DevOps recommends Shift Left because early testing saves time, cost, and improves software quality.

Q2 (c) What is the Main Focus of Automating Security Checks When Shifting Left?
Introduction

The main focus is to detect and fix security issues early and continuously without slowing development.

Key Focus Areas
1. Early Detection of Vulnerabilities

Find flaws while code is being written.

2. Continuous Security Testing

Run checks every time code changes.

3. Reducing Manual Effort

Automation saves time.

4. Fast Feedback

Developers get instant alerts.

5. Consistent Security Rules

Same checks every time.

6. Prevent Insecure Code

Stops risky code before deployment.

Example

If a developer uploads insecure code, the system automatically blocks the build.

Conclusion

Automating security checks in Shift Left improves speed, security, and software quality.
